    "content": "{\"user_message\": \"\", \"command_output\": {\"stdout\": \"Vulnerability on My Android Hotspot\\nPramodh Cyb\\nPramodh Cyb\\n\\nFollow\\n3 min read\\n\\u00b7\\nJul 17, 2025\\n2\\n\\n\\n\\n\\nHere\\u2019s What I Learned\\n\\nRecently, while experimenting with network scanning in my home lab, I stumbled upon something unexpected on my Android hotspot.\\n\\nI was running Nmap inside my Kali Linux VM to explore the devices on my local network. My goal was simple \\u2014 just see what\\u2019s online. But what I discovered opened my eyes to how even a simple mobile hotspot can expose hidden risks.\\n\\nDiscovering the Device\\nFirst, I scanned my entire LAN:\\n\\nsudo nmap -sn (MYIP)\\nI found a few devices:\\n\\nPress enter or click to view image in full size\\n\\nMy Windows PC\\n\\nMy Kali VM itself\\n\\nAnd an interesting thing (MYIP)(the hotspot gateway)\\n\\nSo I decided to scan it in detail:\\n\\nsudo nmap -A MYIP\\nThe result?\\n\\n\\n53/tcp open  domain  dnsmasq 2.51\\nDevice type: phone\\nRunning: Google Android 6.X|7.X, Linux 3.X|4.X\\nOnly one port was open \\u2014 Port 53 (DNS), running an old version of dnsmasq 2.51.\\n\\nWhy Port 53 Caught My Attention\\nPort 53 is the DNS service, which resolves domain names to IPs.\\nIf DNS is compromised, attackers can silently redirect your traffic \\u2014 making phishing almost invisible.\\n\\nAnd dnsmasq 2.51? That\\u2019s ancient.\\n\\nPress enter or click to view image in full size\\n\\nI looked it up and found it was vulnerable to multiple CVEs, including:\\n\\nCVE-2017\\u201314491 \\u2014 Remote Code Execution\\n\\nCVE-2017\\u201314492 \\u2014 Denial of Service\\n\\nCVE-2017\\u201314493 \\u2014 Heap Overflow \\u2192 Code Execution\\n\\nThis meant anyone connected to the same hotspot could potentially:\\n\\u2705 Poison the DNS cache\\n\\u2705 Redirect all users to fake websites\\n\\u2705 Crash the hotspot\\n\\u2705 Or even execute malicious code\\n\\nSimulating the Risk\\nI wanted to understand how easy it would be for an attacker to abuse this.\\n\\nGet Pramodh Cyb\\u2019s stories in your inbox\\nJoin Medium for free to get updates from this writer.\\n\\nEnter your email\\nSubscribe\\n\\nRemember me for faster sign in\\n\\nSo, in my test lab, I set up a simple DNS spoofing attack using Bettercap:\\n\\nsudo bettercap -iface eth0\\nset dns.spoof.all true\\nset dns.spoof.domains google.com\\nset dns.spoof.address \\ndns.spoof on\\nAny device connected to the hotspot that tried to visit google.com was silently redirected to a fake page I hosted.\\n\\nIt was shockingly easy.\", \"stderr\": \"\", \"returncode\": 0}, \"steps\": [\"Read the article summary to understand the vulnerability\", \"Research dnsmasq 2.51 vulnerability details and exploitation method\", \"Check local environment for required tools (dnsmasq, iptables, etc.)\", \"Design the tool architecture (scan gateway, check version, perform DNS poisoning/redirect)\", \"Implement the tool in Python\", \"Test the tool in a safe environment (e.g., local VM or container)\", \"Provide final tool to user\"], \"current_step\": \"Read the article summary to understand the vulnerability\"}"
